# Private app slug denylist — FORMAT TEMPLATE (not a working denylist).
#
# This tracked file documents the FORMAT of the denylist only. It must
# never contain a real private slug, and it must never contain a token
# that legitimately appears elsewhere in this open-source repo — the
# guard scans the whole tree, so a colliding token here causes a false
# CI failure.
#
# Where the REAL denylist lives:
#   - Local pre-commit hook (maintainers): the gitignored `.private-slugs`
#     file at the repo root. Copy this file to `.private-slugs` and
#     replace the sentinels below with your real private slugs.
#   - CI enforcement: the `PRIVATE_SLUGS` GitHub Actions repository
#     secret (newline-separated). The private-slug-guard workflow writes
#     the secret to `.private-slugs` at runtime, then scans. If the
#     secret is not configured, CI prints a skip notice and passes —
#     forks and contributor PRs are never blocked by a missing secret.
#
# Format:
#   - one slug per line
#   - blank lines and `#` comments are ignored
#   - each line is a case-insensitive regex fragment, matched as a
#     word-ish token (so a slug will not match a longer surrounding word)
#   - escape regex metacharacters: write a literal dot as `\.`
#
# The guard FAILS CLOSED: if `.private-slugs` is present but empty when
# run in CI / `--all` mode, it exits non-zero rather than passing.
#
# The entries below are SENTINELS — obvious non-tokens that cannot occur
# in real repo content. Replace every line with your real private slugs
# in your local `.private-slugs` (and in the `PRIVATE_SLUGS` secret).
your-private-app-name
your-private-app-ios
your-private-app-web
your-company-domain\.example
